//01. Change the Color of Text
<h2 style="color: red;">CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p>Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>
</main>

//Note that it is a good practice to end inline style declarations with a ; .


//02. Use CSS Selectors to Style Elements
<style> 
  h2 { 
    color: blue;
  } 
</style>
<h2>CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p>Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>
</main>

/*Note that it's important to have both opening and closing curly braces ({ and }) around each element's style rule(s). 
You also need to make sure that your element's style definition is between the opening and closing style tags. 
Finally, be sure to add a semicolon to the end of each of your element's style rules.*/


//03. Use a CSS Class to Style an Element
<style>
  .red-text {
    color: red;
  }
</style>
<h2 class="red-text">CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p>Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>
</main>

//Note that in your CSS style element, class names start with a period. In your HTML elements' class attribute, the class name does not include the period.


//04. Style Multiple Elements with a CSS Class
<style>
  .red-text {
    color: red;
  }
</style>
<h2 class="red-text">CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p class="red-text">Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>
</main>


//05. Change the Font Size of an Element
<style>
  .red-text {
    color: red;
  }
  p {
  font-size: 16px;
}
</style>
<h2 class="red-text">CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p class="red-text">Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>
</main>


//06. Set the Font Family of an Element
<style>
  .red-text {
    color: red;
  }
  p {
  font-size: 16px;
  font-family: monospace;
}
</style>
<h2 class="red-text">CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p>Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>
</main>


//07. Import a Google Font
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Lobster" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css">
<style>
  h2 {
    font-family: Lobster;
  }
  p {
    font-size: 16px;
    font-family: monospace;
  }
</style>
<h2>CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p>Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>
</main>

//To import a Google Font, you can copy the font's URL from the Google Fonts library and then paste it in your HTML.


//08. Specify How Fonts Should Degrade
<!--<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Lobster" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css">-->
<style>
  .red-text {
    color: red;
  }
  h2 {
    font-family: Lobster, monospace;
  }
  p {
    font-size: 16px;
    font-family: monospace;
  }
</style>
<h2 class="red-text">CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p class="red-text">Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>
</main>


//09. Size Your Images
<link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Lobster" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css">
<style>
  .smaller-image {
    width: 100px;
  }
  .red-text {
    color: red;
  }
  h2 {
    font-family: Lobster, monospace;
  }
  p {
    font-size: 16px;
    font-family: monospace;
  }
</style>
<h2 class="red-text">CatPhotoApp</h2>
<main>
  <p class="red-text">Click here to view more <a href="#">cat photos</a>.</p>
<a href="#"><img class="smaller-image" src="https://cdn.freecodecamp.org/curriculum/cat-photo-app/relaxing-cat.jpg" alt="A cute orange cat lying on its back."></a>
</main>


//10. Add Borders Around Your Elements
